1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,900
Are you ready to dig into the Word of the Lord today? I hope so.

2
00:00:05,660 --> 00:00:10,080
We're in a series on kingdom living and kind of asking the question,

3
00:00:10,300 --> 00:00:15,040
what does an authentic Christian look like in different areas of our lives?

4
00:00:15,800 --> 00:00:20,480
It's one thing to come and worship and sing and do things here, but what happens when we leave?

5
00:00:20,640 --> 00:00:25,760
What difference does Christ make in the different dimensions of our lives outside these walls?

6
00:00:26,700 --> 00:00:30,860
And so we've been looking at that, and this morning we're looking at a topic that I'm

7
00:00:30,860 --> 00:00:35,980
kind of anxious and excited to preach about, probably because I'm the greatest offender.

8
00:00:37,120 --> 00:00:42,420
And so this one is really pointed at me primarily, and I hope you learn something as well, okay?

9
00:00:43,490 --> 00:00:48,930
Because I've not met too many committed followers of Jesus who were lazy and slothful.

10
00:00:49,470 --> 00:00:51,030
In fact, it's the opposite.

11
00:00:51,210 --> 00:00:55,070
I've found that too many Christians are wound up, stressed out, and overcommitted.

12
00:00:55,070 --> 00:00:58,680
Does that resonate with anybody in this room besides me?

13
00:00:59,840 --> 00:01:00,680
Okay, a few of you.

14
00:01:00,720 --> 00:01:01,800
You're going to be honest, okay.

15
00:01:03,350 --> 00:01:06,970
Tim Hansel in a book called When I Relax, I Feel Guilty said this.

16
00:01:08,910 --> 00:01:15,150
So many Christians have succumbed to busyness, unhappiness, tightness, and boredom.

17
00:01:16,250 --> 00:01:22,490
Many suffer from a nagging sense of guilt that no matter how much they do, it's never quite enough.

18
00:01:23,580 --> 00:01:27,680
Words like wonder, joy, rest, and freedom

19
00:01:27,680 --> 00:01:31,440
have become faded replicas of what Christ taught.

20
00:01:32,620 --> 00:01:34,980
Time becomes a tyrant instead of a friend.

21
00:01:35,760 --> 00:01:38,040
Joy becomes something we will do later.

22
00:01:38,780 --> 00:01:41,120
Play becomes something only for children.

23
00:01:42,190 --> 00:01:46,210
Creativity becomes the unattainable quality of artists and poets

24
00:01:46,210 --> 00:01:48,950
instead of the essence of our lives.

25
00:01:49,770 --> 00:01:51,530
Wonder is the name of a bread,

26
00:01:51,530 --> 00:01:56,770
and imagination doesn't make enough money to be worthwhile.

27
00:01:58,320 --> 00:02:03,060
Committed followers of Jesus Christ in America, by and large, have a good work ethic,

28
00:02:03,060 --> 00:02:07,340
but I'm not sure that we're convinced that we are to play.

29
00:02:09,430 --> 00:02:11,510
Does godliness equal busyness?

30
00:02:13,520 --> 00:02:17,620
We've got a work ethic, but do we have a rest ethic?

31
00:02:20,220 --> 00:02:21,860
Can rest and leisure be holy?

32
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:23,220
Is recreation godly?

33
00:02:23,600 --> 00:02:25,700
What should our recreation look like?

34
00:02:25,700 --> 00:02:33,880
as Christians? And given that we live in a locale that is just so full of opportunities for fun,

35
00:02:33,880 --> 00:02:40,140
recreation, and leisure, what difference does our faith in Jesus Christ make in our rest if we ever

36
00:02:40,140 --> 00:02:47,940
take it and our relaxation at all? Some of you might resonate with some of this. Is your schedule

37
00:02:47,940 --> 00:02:56,570
overwhelming? Do you find yourself at times tempted to brag about how your schedule is

38
00:02:56,570 --> 00:03:02,030
overwhelming. Do your children and grandchildren seem disoriented

39
00:03:02,030 --> 00:03:07,760
when not on the way somewhere? When you call your kids for dinner,

40
00:03:07,880 --> 00:03:16,700
do they instinctively jump in the minivan? Does life seem like it's

41
00:03:16,700 --> 00:03:20,760
just one activity after another? It's hockey and then soccer

42
00:03:20,760 --> 00:03:24,800
and basketball and homework and tennis and piano and ballet and on

43
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:28,800
and on and on. Does that seem to resonate with either your life or

44
00:03:28,800 --> 00:03:32,660
your kid's life or grandchildren? Studies are

45
00:03:32,660 --> 00:03:39,040
shown us in the last 20 years has been a decline of 12 hours a week in the average child's free

46
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:45,740
time. We're filling up their lives, and we're filling up our lives as parents and grandparents.

47
00:03:45,740 --> 00:03:54,630
Is that always a good thing? In American families, time for household conversation has decreased

48
00:03:54,630 --> 00:04:03,430
by 100%. Even though studies show that that's the number one preventative of at-risk behavior

49
00:04:03,430 --> 00:04:13,540
is conversation. We're not doing it with our kids and our grandkids. In a national poll in the year

50
00:04:13,540 --> 00:04:22,240
2000, educational issues tied with not having enough time together with parents, those two

51
00:04:22,240 --> 00:04:29,800
issues were the chief concerns among teenagers in our country. And I found this interesting in light

52
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:34,280
especially of our guest this morning. In 1997, there was a study by the International Labor

53
00:04:34,280 --> 00:04:40,740
organization, that Americans work more hours than even the Japanese, and that I've always thought

54
00:04:40,740 --> 00:04:45,980
of the Japanese as the most industrious working nation, and yet Americans are now working more

55
00:04:45,980 --> 00:04:55,190
and playing less. Why do we live such harried, rushed, frantic lives? And the deeper question

56
00:04:55,190 --> 00:05:01,100
might be, why do some of us fear that school is out? Because we can't keep them occupied till

57
00:05:01,100 --> 00:05:08,110
September, maybe. See, we're so used to this fast pace. Does life have to be this complicated?

58
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:18,280
Is this the abundant life that Jesus promised his followers? Does godliness equal busyness?

59
00:05:18,840 --> 00:05:24,360
Let's start in the Scriptures with Exodus chapter 20. I share it with you.

60
00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:34,000
Remember, God says, to observe the Sabbath day by keeping it holy. Six days a week are set apart

61
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,140
for your daily duties and regular work,

62
00:05:36,440 --> 00:05:38,980
but the seventh day is a day of rest

63
00:05:38,980 --> 00:05:41,040
dedicated to the Lord your God.

64
00:05:41,910 --> 00:05:44,210
On that day, no one in your household

65
00:05:44,210 --> 00:05:45,690
may do any kind of work.

66
00:05:46,270 --> 00:05:48,550
This includes you, your sons and daughters,

67
00:05:48,730 --> 00:05:49,910
male and female servants,

68
00:05:49,910 --> 00:05:53,170
your livestock, and any foreigners living among you.

69
00:05:53,830 --> 00:05:56,270
For in six days the Lord made the heavens,

70
00:05:56,430 --> 00:05:59,410
the earth, the sea, and everything in them.

71
00:06:00,140 --> 00:06:02,480
Then he rested on the seventh day.

72
00:06:03,600 --> 00:06:08,400
That is why the Lord blessed the Sabbath day and set it apart as holy.

73
00:06:10,980 --> 00:06:13,220
Now as we look at that text, coming from the Old Testament,

74
00:06:13,620 --> 00:06:18,900
we need to realize that God didn't rest on the seventh day because he was tired.

75
00:06:20,630 --> 00:06:25,530
It's easy to put that concept onto God as if, boy, six days of creating the universe,

76
00:06:25,530 --> 00:06:29,310
and wow, God is tired, God's pooped out, he takes a break.

77
00:06:29,470 --> 00:06:33,330
I don't think that's the concept here in the text.

78
00:06:33,330 --> 00:06:38,140
because he desisted from work on the seventh day

79
00:06:38,140 --> 00:06:40,800
and entered into the enjoyment of what he had.

80
00:06:40,800 --> 00:06:46,440
The seventh day was to experience the goodness of the creation.

81
00:06:48,320 --> 00:06:50,320
It was a time for play with the creation.

82
00:06:50,760 --> 00:06:55,200
A time for Sabbath rest means that we are to enter into that mutual enjoyment

83
00:06:55,200 --> 00:06:58,040
of God and of his good creation.

84
00:06:58,760 --> 00:07:01,060
That's the heart behind the Sabbath.

85
00:07:01,060 --> 00:07:05,750
I love this text from Mark chapter 6.

86
00:07:07,600 --> 00:07:14,200
The apostles returned to Jesus from their ministry tour and told him all that they had done and what they had taught.

87
00:07:15,410 --> 00:07:20,110
Then Jesus said, let's get away from the crowds for a while and rest.

88
00:07:21,440 --> 00:07:26,720
There were so many people coming and going that Jesus and the apostles didn't even have time to eat.

89
00:07:27,360 --> 00:07:30,600
They left by boat for a quieter spot.

90
00:07:31,980 --> 00:07:36,360
Jesus took a break, and I'm getting convicted, all right?

91
00:07:37,250 --> 00:07:38,450
I hope some of you are too.

92
00:07:41,140 --> 00:07:45,540
Another passage, another image for us to ponder in our text this morning, Zechariah chapter 8.

93
00:07:47,330 --> 00:07:49,750
Another message came from the Lord Almighty.

94
00:07:51,050 --> 00:07:52,950
This is what the Lord Almighty says.

95
00:07:52,950 --> 00:07:56,330
My love for Mount Zion is passionate and strong.

96
00:07:57,170 --> 00:07:59,770
I am consumed with passion for Jerusalem.

97
00:08:00,630 --> 00:08:04,550
Then Jerusalem, and now the Lord says, I'm returning to Mount Zion.

98
00:08:04,670 --> 00:08:06,210
I will live in Jerusalem.

99
00:08:06,210 --> 00:08:09,390
Then Jerusalem will be called the faithful city.

100
00:08:09,930 --> 00:08:13,310
The mountain of the Lord Almighty will be called the holy mountain.

101
00:08:14,150 --> 00:08:16,150
This is what the Lord Almighty says.

102
00:08:16,510 --> 00:08:21,690
Once again, old men and women will walk Jerusalem's streets with a cane

103
00:08:21,690 --> 00:08:24,090
and sit together in the city squares.

104
00:08:24,730 --> 00:08:28,710
And the streets of the city will be filled with, notice this,

105
00:08:28,710 --> 00:08:31,470
boys and girls at play.

106
00:08:32,760 --> 00:08:33,400
Isn't that beautiful?

107
00:08:35,200 --> 00:08:38,400
The streets of the city are filled with boys and girls at play.

108
00:08:38,700 --> 00:08:39,700
What a wonderful image.

109
00:08:39,700 --> 00:08:46,320
The first hearers of that prophecy knew their sordid history.

110
00:08:47,810 --> 00:08:51,810
The kingdom of Israel had been for years under King David,

111
00:08:52,130 --> 00:08:55,270
and it was a glorious time, and that was five centuries before.

112
00:08:55,930 --> 00:09:00,110
But then the kingdom was divided, and the northern kingdom was destroyed,

113
00:09:00,110 --> 00:09:01,890
and there was the Assyrians that came in,

114
00:09:01,950 --> 00:09:04,090
the Babylonians, there was an exile

115
00:09:04,090 --> 00:09:08,560
and finally a remnant is allowed to come back

116
00:09:08,560 --> 00:09:12,940
to Jerusalem and all they could see

117
00:09:12,940 --> 00:09:14,300
was a barren wasteland.

118
00:09:14,720 --> 00:09:16,620
But God communicates this image

119
00:09:16,620 --> 00:09:19,080
of restoration of hope

120
00:09:19,080 --> 00:09:21,080
and a wonderful future that's coming

121
00:09:21,080 --> 00:09:24,200
and the image is children involved

122
00:09:24,200 --> 00:09:25,860
in frivolous play.

123
00:09:27,210 --> 00:09:27,850
Isn't that beautiful?

124
00:09:28,900 --> 00:09:31,240
The image of restoration are the children

125
00:09:31,240 --> 00:09:43,090
at play. It's an image of peace and an image of blessing. Carefree play is a blessing of God.

126
00:09:43,470 --> 00:09:50,400
Whether you're young or you're old, that's a blessing of God on our lives. But so often we

127
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:57,540
squander that blessing, we get over committed, we fail to build margin into our lives, and we get

128
00:09:57,540 --> 00:10:04,600
crowded by the things of the world, and we wear busyness as a badge of honor and a sign of our

129
00:10:04,600 --> 00:10:12,020
self-importance. Sometimes we even turn our play and our children's play into work. It's been said,

130
00:10:12,080 --> 00:10:18,990
I love this phrase, we worship our work, we work at our play, and we play at our worship.

131
00:10:20,200 --> 00:10:26,810
We have it all upside down. We get things out of balance. We need rest. We need leisure and play

132
00:10:26,810 --> 00:10:29,950
to be healthy in our bodies and our souls.

133
00:10:31,380 --> 00:10:32,780
I looked up the word leisure,

134
00:10:34,020 --> 00:10:36,580
and I noticed it came from the same Latin root

135
00:10:36,580 --> 00:10:38,820
from where you get the word license.

136
00:10:40,110 --> 00:10:42,710
And so the word license means to permit.

137
00:10:43,960 --> 00:10:45,480
Leisure is, in a sense,

138
00:10:45,980 --> 00:10:49,560
permitting yourself to do the things you don't normally do.

139
00:10:51,140 --> 00:10:53,480
We give ourselves permission to be free,

140
00:10:54,890 --> 00:10:56,710
free to play like carefree children.

141
00:10:59,120 --> 00:11:03,940
In my research, I also found that the early Puritans that settled our country,

142
00:11:03,940 --> 00:11:07,480
we tend to think of them as really dour, uptight people.

143
00:11:07,920 --> 00:11:10,620
You know, the belt buckle on their hats and the whole thing.

144
00:11:11,240 --> 00:11:16,640
And we have this image that they just were strict and didn't know how to have any kind of fun.

145
00:11:16,980 --> 00:11:20,620
And yet I discovered that Richard Rogers, one of the earliest of the Puritans,

146
00:11:20,940 --> 00:11:23,720
actually advocated and taught this schedule.

147
00:11:24,220 --> 00:11:25,000
I love this.

148
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:31,200
He says, we're to make up eight hours of our day for work, eight hours a day for sleep,

149
00:11:31,560 --> 00:11:36,960
and eight hours a day for relaxation with friends, with books, or the creation.

150
00:11:38,140 --> 00:11:39,220
Doesn't that sound balanced?

151
00:11:39,940 --> 00:11:40,940
Doesn't that sound wonderful?

152
00:11:42,020 --> 00:11:44,860
Eight hours of work, eight hours of sleep, eight hours of recreation.

153
00:11:46,050 --> 00:11:48,630
Wow, sign me up.

154
00:11:52,470 --> 00:11:56,040
We don't think of God as one who plays.

155
00:11:57,900 --> 00:12:04,240
And as we've talked about before, the films in Hollywood often portray Jesus also as really serious and really dour.

156
00:12:04,680 --> 00:12:07,040
We don't see the frivolity in Jesus.

157
00:12:07,040 --> 00:12:17,160
We don't see the relationships and the smiles and the joy he takes in being with people, with his disciples, with Mary and Martha and Lazarus.

158
00:12:17,220 --> 00:12:20,520
We don't see him portrayed in that way.

159
00:12:22,140 --> 00:12:26,400
The Song of Songs, though, has this playful sexuality all throughout the text.

160
00:12:26,400 --> 00:12:37,420
The Old Testament, we see festivals and dances and celebrations of God's people as a normal part of the experience of living under God in that context.

161
00:12:38,520 --> 00:12:42,460
We see Jesus' first miracle of wine at a wedding feast.

162
00:12:43,960 --> 00:12:51,160
Those things tell us something about God and about playfulness and about recreation and rest.

163
00:12:53,620 --> 00:12:58,160
Here's four things I want to say that doing nothing is good for a variety of reasons.

164
00:12:58,160 --> 00:13:05,730
number one, rest and recreation give us a diversion. They give us a diversion from our

165
00:13:05,730 --> 00:13:13,510
normal employment. They allow us to break our routines. You notice that when you really get

166
00:13:13,510 --> 00:13:18,970
involved in play, when you really get a chance to play, that time stands completely still.

167
00:13:20,190 --> 00:13:26,230
You are totally removed from the normal routines and time and everything else and your cares and

168
00:13:26,230 --> 00:13:33,510
worries just completely vanish. I think of probably the most memorable moment of play

169
00:13:33,510 --> 00:13:41,280
that just has seared itself into my mind. And I have to confess, I need to take more notice of

170
00:13:41,280 --> 00:13:46,260
those moments, but this one is sort of the granddaddy of them all. When I was in college,

171
00:13:46,260 --> 00:13:52,200
about 20 of us drove to Mammoth Mountain on a snowy weekend in January, Martin Luther King

172
00:13:52,200 --> 00:13:58,250
weekend. 20 of us in a condo at Mammoth. If any of you have condos and you have college students

173
00:13:58,250 --> 00:14:05,300
coming, beware. The place, I think, actually slept six, but there were 20 of us there, some in the

174
00:14:05,300 --> 00:14:11,320
bathtub on the kitchen floor. It was really, you know, $10 a head wasn't bad, but it was quite the

175
00:14:11,320 --> 00:14:16,160
time. Now, most of my friends there were drunk as skunks, and they were hung over that next morning,

176
00:14:16,160 --> 00:14:20,740
and I was the good Christian. I was like, no way with that, and me and two friends, we got up

177
00:14:20,740 --> 00:14:25,960
early after the storm had broke and we got up there we were some of the first ones in line we

178
00:14:25,960 --> 00:14:31,950
were the first ones on that lift all the way to the top and we could still hear them you know

179
00:14:31,950 --> 00:14:37,470
blasting the mountain to try and get the snow to fall and to start the avalanche if that was needed

180
00:14:37,470 --> 00:14:45,610
because this storm had dumped five to six feet of fresh powder you know those warren miller ski

181
00:14:45,610 --> 00:14:50,850
movies you ever seen one of those i always wonder where they film that stuff where do they get

182
00:14:50,850 --> 00:14:56,150
anybody actually go where the sun is perfect, snow is perfect, the tracks haven't been made.

183
00:14:56,410 --> 00:15:04,020
You know, nobody ever really has that except me that day. And my two friends and I, we got up to

184
00:15:04,020 --> 00:15:09,740
the top of the Scott Bowl, if you know that wonderful mountain. And we jumped into that

185
00:15:09,740 --> 00:15:16,660
thing and landed up to our necks. And we came down that mountain with fresh tracks and the snow

186
00:15:16,660 --> 00:15:25,540
blowing over our heads it was divine and for those moments we were going down that mountain it was

187
00:15:25,540 --> 00:15:35,750
like a moment completely removed from finals from exams from stress from anything it was a holy day

188
00:15:35,750 --> 00:15:43,190
it was it has just seared itself into my conscience as the most amazing moments and i don't think we

189
00:15:43,190 --> 00:15:48,850
take those kinds of times enough to refresh. I left the mountain that day just invigorated in

190
00:15:48,850 --> 00:15:55,790
spirit, in body. I loved God. I loved His creation. I loved the snow and the sunshine and my friends.

191
00:15:57,290 --> 00:16:04,660
We drove back tired but refreshed. Oh, it was so good. Why do we not do that more often

192
00:16:04,660 --> 00:16:10,300
and refresh ourselves? We need diversions. We need those things to keep us healthy and sharp.

193
00:16:11,560 --> 00:16:14,440
Number two, rest and recreation also refresh us.

194
00:16:16,330 --> 00:16:22,640
They provide an opportunity for creative thoughts, to cultivate memories, to gain perspective.

195
00:16:26,110 --> 00:16:30,210
Sometimes vacation times or when I even go up to the mountains and do some writing and

196
00:16:30,210 --> 00:16:37,520
praying and reflecting, it's those times I can see the bigger picture because the details

197
00:16:37,520 --> 00:16:42,380
of the day and the rhythms of the day finally cease for a few moments and you get a chance

198
00:16:42,380 --> 00:16:49,210
to see really what's important, where you're going, where you've been. I think that's healthy

199
00:16:49,210 --> 00:16:53,990
and I come back often with new ideas and new creative thoughts and rejuvenated by spending

200
00:16:53,990 --> 00:17:04,120
time with God without any of the busyness around. It's so refreshing. It's kind of like many of you

201
00:17:04,120 --> 00:17:09,020
work with computers, right? You're used to that. You've experienced either a computer or seen it

202
00:17:09,020 --> 00:17:13,980
done. There are times in the life of a person in front of a computer when the computer freezes,

203
00:17:13,980 --> 00:17:24,180
right? Yeah, you've been there. Locks up, gets stuck, and what do you do? You either hit reset

204
00:17:24,180 --> 00:17:30,920
or the three-finger salute, control, alt, delete, right? That's the salute. When you give the

205
00:17:30,920 --> 00:17:40,680
computer those three fingers, boom, it's all gone and it reboots. That's what rest and Sabbath does

206
00:17:40,680 --> 00:17:47,540
to our spirits. We're crowded, we're locked up, and we're stuck. Control-Alt-Delete, take a break,

207
00:17:47,680 --> 00:17:55,720
it's gone, you start over. God knew what He was doing when He gave the people of Israel a Sabbath.

208
00:17:56,280 --> 00:18:05,830
You're working six days, Control-Alt-Delete, start over and rest and rejuvenate. It's a time for our

209
00:18:05,830 --> 00:18:13,810
hearts, our souls, and our minds to hit the reset key as Sabbath. We get things fresh, reordered,

210
00:18:14,110 --> 00:18:20,540
the memory is cleared. So rest and recreation refresh us. Rest and recreation, number three,

211
00:18:20,620 --> 00:18:27,300
also transform us because they allow us to play and they allow us to enter into that experience

212
00:18:27,300 --> 00:18:34,110
of being childlike in front of God and enjoying His creation. Psalm 37.4 says,

213
00:18:34,690 --> 00:18:42,290
delight yourself in the Lord and He will give you the desires of your heart. That's not a suggestion,

214
00:18:42,290 --> 00:18:43,170
and that's a command.

215
00:18:43,630 --> 00:18:46,610
Delight yourselves in the Lord.

216
00:18:48,710 --> 00:18:49,710
Delight yourself in Him.

217
00:18:50,810 --> 00:18:53,170
Rest and recreation can be part of that experience.

218
00:18:54,950 --> 00:18:58,370
Now in thinking about this issue of rest and recreation,

219
00:18:59,550 --> 00:19:02,210
is all recreation specifically Christian?

220
00:19:02,450 --> 00:19:05,250
What makes Christian recreation?

221
00:19:06,660 --> 00:19:08,680
And I'm indebted to the thinking of Robert Johnston

222
00:19:08,680 --> 00:19:12,080
and R. Paul Stevens in this area of play and recreation.

223
00:19:12,660 --> 00:19:15,020
Because just because we have a basketball

224
00:19:15,020 --> 00:19:19,080
game going in the gym with Christians doesn't necessarily

225
00:19:19,080 --> 00:19:24,990
make that sport spiritual. We've had some competitive games

226
00:19:24,990 --> 00:19:28,730
over there. Juices are flowing. I mean, what makes it Christian? Is it just

227
00:19:28,730 --> 00:19:34,260
because it's on a church campus? I think our recreation

228
00:19:34,260 --> 00:19:38,140
and our rest and our play becomes Christian

229
00:19:38,140 --> 00:19:41,810
because of two things. The character of the action

230
00:19:41,810 --> 00:19:48,280
and the intent of the person. You see, God gave human beings

231
00:19:48,280 --> 00:19:54,760
a three-fold mandate. Live in communion with God, build community amongst His people,

232
00:19:55,220 --> 00:19:59,160
and work with God to cultivate the earth and develop its potential.

233
00:20:00,610 --> 00:20:05,850
And any recreation that we might engage in that somehow erodes our communion with God

234
00:20:05,850 --> 00:20:13,810
is really not something we ought to partake in. Games that toy around with the demonic

235
00:20:13,810 --> 00:20:21,230
or that encourage kind of a predatory kind of competition, I think, are not Christian.

236
00:20:21,230 --> 00:20:29,020
I take Wired Magazine to keep me up on what's going on, and there's all these reviews of

237
00:20:29,020 --> 00:20:40,700
these computer games full of violence and death and destruction, and this stuff is sick.

238
00:20:43,450 --> 00:20:47,610
Those games, I think, violate our relationship with God.

239
00:20:48,690 --> 00:20:51,430
I think they violate our relationship with each other.

240
00:20:51,430 --> 00:20:57,500
There's this predatory desire that is created when you play some of this stuff.

241
00:20:57,760 --> 00:21:02,460
and so I'm going to challenge us, and it's probably not as appropriate in this congregation.

242
00:21:02,640 --> 00:21:06,540
I don't see many of you going home playing, you know, Doom 4,

243
00:21:07,060 --> 00:21:12,190
but certainly next service I'm going to let them have it, okay, just so you know.

244
00:21:13,370 --> 00:21:16,890
Because those kinds of experiences do not honor God.

245
00:21:17,010 --> 00:21:19,170
I think that they are recreation.

246
00:21:19,570 --> 00:21:25,470
They take a break from reality, but the reality you're creating in the experience is not of God.

247
00:21:26,310 --> 00:21:28,030
And we as Christians need to be critical

248
00:21:28,030 --> 00:21:31,160
and thinking about the things that we engage in.

249
00:21:31,220 --> 00:21:33,100
Are these things honoring God and people

250
00:21:33,100 --> 00:21:36,480
or are they destructive in some way?

251
00:21:37,630 --> 00:21:39,710
Recreation that endangers the creation, I think,

252
00:21:39,790 --> 00:21:42,050
is also something that we need to ask ourselves

253
00:21:42,050 --> 00:21:44,550
if taking a four-wheel drive

254
00:21:44,550 --> 00:21:47,150
and running right over the rabbits is a good thing or not.

255
00:21:48,050 --> 00:21:49,330
We have to ask some questions there.

256
00:21:53,200 --> 00:21:54,560
So that's the character of the action

257
00:21:54,560 --> 00:21:57,600
is what we're doing violating the creation

258
00:21:57,600 --> 00:21:59,460
or violating God's personhood

259
00:21:59,460 --> 00:22:00,880
or our relationship with each other.

260
00:22:01,880 --> 00:22:03,700
And there's also the intent of the person.

261
00:22:05,880 --> 00:22:09,720
If we're doing recreation according to God's plan,

262
00:22:10,840 --> 00:22:13,160
we're not doing it,

263
00:22:14,340 --> 00:22:15,360
rather let me say it this way,

264
00:22:15,360 --> 00:22:18,890
we're playing in grace.

265
00:22:19,470 --> 00:22:21,950
We're allowing ourselves to experience grace.

266
00:22:22,370 --> 00:22:24,310
We allow ourselves to take a break

267
00:22:24,310 --> 00:22:27,390
because we understand that God has saved us

268
00:22:27,390 --> 00:22:29,590
by grace, not by works.

269
00:22:30,250 --> 00:22:31,870
The Bible says in Ephesians 2, 8, 9,

270
00:22:31,950 --> 00:22:33,850
it's by grace you've been saved through faith

271
00:22:33,850 --> 00:22:35,610
and this not from yourselves,

272
00:22:35,930 --> 00:22:37,210
it's the gift of God,

273
00:22:37,810 --> 00:22:40,150
not by work so that no one can boast.

274
00:22:41,760 --> 00:22:43,600
If we fail to take time off

275
00:22:43,600 --> 00:22:45,180
to have some recreation,

276
00:22:45,320 --> 00:22:46,460
to restore ourselves,

277
00:22:46,640 --> 00:22:48,960
we're really not living under grace yet

278
00:22:48,960 --> 00:22:51,590
because we don't really trust

279
00:22:51,590 --> 00:22:52,890
that God is in control

280
00:22:52,890 --> 00:22:55,400
or that somehow we're good enough.

281
00:22:55,500 --> 00:22:57,060
You see, friends, we're never good enough.

282
00:22:57,060 --> 00:22:58,460
We're saved by grace.

283
00:22:58,460 --> 00:23:01,880
and by working a little harder and working more

284
00:23:01,880 --> 00:23:05,540
and always doing more is not what God has for us.

285
00:23:07,140 --> 00:23:09,040
He wants us to rest.

286
00:23:10,480 --> 00:23:14,420
He mandated the Israelites rest at least once every seven days.

287
00:23:17,170 --> 00:23:19,430
In recreation and play, we don't earn anything.

288
00:23:20,280 --> 00:23:24,300
We do it wholeheartedly because we are already justified,

289
00:23:24,800 --> 00:23:27,240
freed, and loved in Christ.

290
00:23:29,720 --> 00:23:34,060
We're free then to enjoy God, His creation, and other people.

291
00:23:35,440 --> 00:23:39,600
Another thing I love about recreation is it's a chance to bond with other people.

292
00:23:41,050 --> 00:23:45,570
That's why it's important that we as a fellowship not only worship together and study together,

293
00:23:45,570 --> 00:23:47,190
but play together.

294
00:23:47,990 --> 00:23:48,950
It builds bonds.

295
00:23:49,270 --> 00:23:50,190
It connects us.

296
00:23:50,810 --> 00:23:53,450
And that's part of God's plan for our lives as well.

297
00:23:53,830 --> 00:23:59,130
He wants us to be praying and studying and playing and enjoying Him and the creation together.

298
00:23:59,130 --> 00:24:02,840
it's a way of restoring us

299
00:24:02,840 --> 00:24:03,820
it's an act of worship

300
00:24:03,820 --> 00:24:05,740
to enjoy God

301
00:24:05,740 --> 00:24:09,260
so finally I just want to ask this question

302
00:24:09,260 --> 00:24:11,370
after all of this

303
00:24:11,370 --> 00:24:13,800
are you ready now to go outside

304
00:24:13,800 --> 00:24:15,220
and play

305
00:24:15,220 --> 00:24:18,220
will you make this Sunday

306
00:24:18,220 --> 00:24:20,020
a day of play

307
00:24:20,020 --> 00:24:21,880
enjoying each other

308
00:24:21,880 --> 00:24:23,900
enjoying God and his creation

309
00:24:23,900 --> 00:24:24,980
let's pray

310
00:24:24,980 --> 00:24:25,920
Father thank you

311
00:24:25,920 --> 00:24:30,060
that you save us by grace

312
00:24:30,060 --> 00:24:33,280
you poured out your love upon us

313
00:24:33,280 --> 00:24:35,020
there's nothing we can do to earn it

314
00:24:37,100 --> 00:24:38,180
And so, Lord, we say thank you.

315
00:24:39,080 --> 00:24:42,000
So, Lord, free us to understand that,

316
00:24:42,060 --> 00:24:44,740
to not work ourselves to the bone,

317
00:24:44,840 --> 00:24:46,860
but to experience rest and restoration

318
00:24:46,860 --> 00:24:50,160
and peace and goodness that comes from your hand.

319
00:24:51,470 --> 00:24:53,950
And I pray that our recreation, our time of play

320
00:24:53,950 --> 00:24:56,690
and freedom and enjoying each other

321
00:24:56,690 --> 00:24:59,310
would be honoring to you and to the family of God.

322
00:25:00,980 --> 00:25:02,340
So, Lord, teach us in these areas.

323
00:25:03,160 --> 00:25:03,800
Grow us up.

324
00:25:04,420 --> 00:25:07,700
Allow us and bless us with freedom to play.

325
00:25:07,900 --> 00:25:13,100
And I pray we'd be childlike in front of you, for you are our heavenly Father.

326
00:25:13,860 --> 00:25:18,300
You desire that we come to you in innocence and with a childlike faith.

327
00:25:19,930 --> 00:25:22,850
Lord, may we experience that also in our play and our recreation.

328
00:25:26,100 --> 00:25:30,480
So, Father, I pray you pour out a blessing, a continual blessing on this church and congregation,

329
00:25:31,780 --> 00:25:37,080
that you'd bless them in their play, in their time of restoring and renewal.

330
00:25:38,030 --> 00:25:39,290
It'd be a rich time.

331
00:25:40,070 --> 00:25:41,810
They would take it as a regular time.

332
00:25:41,810 --> 00:25:44,480
you'd honor them in that

333
00:25:44,480 --> 00:25:46,800
that they would honor you in that

334
00:25:46,800 --> 00:25:50,870
that you'd be blessed in our time of refreshment

335
00:25:50,870 --> 00:25:53,400
thank you for these scriptures

336
00:25:53,400 --> 00:25:54,400
and these words

337
00:25:54,400 --> 00:25:55,960
and our time together

338
00:25:55,960 --> 00:25:58,160
we love you in Jesus name

339
00:25:58,160 --> 00:25:59,440
Amen

